<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05013h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05013h">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05013h"> 13(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> A-dam (Pa &amp; Ma)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In the old Akkadian speech, which preceded the Babylonian, and in which a great deal of the Assyrian and Jewish cosmogony was first written, <i>ad</i> signifies a &ldquo;father,&rdquo; and <i>dam</i> &ldquo;mother.&rdquo; Mr. Wake suggests, therefore, that <mark>Adam</mark> was a compound formation, expressing a dual idea, agreeably to the statement as to the first man being &ldquo;<mark>male-female</mark>,&rdquo; and to the Persian tradition which made him androgynous. <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [The Creation Story] 22</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
